      "content": "You're welcome! Since you've identified the joists, you're on the right track, but checking the foundation is the next critical step to ensure the whole structure is stable.\n\nIn the basement or crawlspace, look for the **footing** or **foundation wall** directly beneath the wall you are considering removing. If the wall sits directly on top of a continuous concrete foundation or a solid footing, it is almost certainly load-bearing. You want to see if the wall is anchored into the ground; if it's just a standalone block sitting on top of other walls, it's likely a partition.\n\nAdditionally, check for **sill plates** (the metal or wooden plates that attach the wall to the foundation). If the sill plate is bolted securely to a concrete foundation, that wall is carrying the weight of the house. If you find a beam connecting two load-bearing walls, that wall is definitely part of the structural frame.\n\nFinally, always consult a licensed structural engineer before making any changes. They can review your blueprints and perform a physical inspection to give you a definitive \"yes\" or \"no\" on whether the wall can be safely removed.",
